ted builds a much-needed framework for understanding translation's effect on fictional works, as well as digital art, avant-garde magazines, literary anthologies, and visual media. Artists and novelists discussed include J. M. Coetzee, Junot Díaz, Jonathan Safran Foer, Mohsin Hamid, Kazuo Ishiguro, Jamaica Kincaid, Ben Lerner, China Miéville, David Mitchell, Walter Mosley, Caryl Phillips, Adam Thirlwell, Amy Waldman, and Young-hae Chang Heavy Industries. The book understands that contemporary literature begins at once in many places, engaging in a new type of social embeddedness and political solidarity. It recasts literary history as a series of convergences and departures and, by elevating the status of "born-translated" works, redefines common conceptions of author, reader, and nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFictionvTranslationsxHistory and criticism. 0aLiteraturexTranslationsxHistory and criticism. 0aTranslating and interpreting. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070982708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/walk1659440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231539456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231539456/original  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-070982-7  CUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles